<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1108,1900]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,394,1108,1134]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[404,633,1108,1133]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Potamobates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shuar">
<emphasis box="[404,633,1108,1133]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Potamobates shuar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[999,1150,1108,1133]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Potamobates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anchicaya">
<emphasis box="[999,1150,1108,1133]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">P. anchicaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having a single lateral spine on the right side of the male’s VIII abdominal segment (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2. A, B" captionStartId="3.[264,368,860,884]" captionTargetBox="[470,1131,314,845]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[448,1145,306,871]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A, B: Potamobates shuar n. sp.; A: male genital segment, ventral view; B: male genital segment, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173727/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,280,1188,1214]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName box="[355,503,1188,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Potamobates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anchicaya">
<emphasis box="[355,503,1188,1213]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">P. anchicaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the male has two lateral spines on the right side of the VIII abdominal segment. In the female 
<emphasis box="[539,638,1228,1253]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName box="[539,635,1228,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Potamobates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shuar">P. shuar</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the connexiva (
<figureCitation box="[826,892,1228,1254]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[377,1217,608,1718]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[370,1226,603,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: habitat of P. horvathi and P. anchicaya in locality Montalvo, La Mayronga (photo F. M. Buzzetti); B: habitat of P. shuar n. sp. in locality Bomboiza (photo P. Tirello); C: P. s h u a r n. sp. female abdomen in dorsal view (photo F. M. Buzzetti); D: P. s h u a r n. sp. male holotype (photo F. M. Buzzetti)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[881,892,1228,1254]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
C) almost join at the level of the last two abdominal segments, whereas in the 
<taxonomicName box="[780,936,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Potamobates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anchicaya">
<emphasis box="[780,936,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">P. anchicaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female the connexiva are well separated all along the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,1108,1900]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1321,284,550]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,466,1348,1374]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Description:</emphasis>
Apterous male (
<typeStatus box="[667,797,1348,1374]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Holotypus</typeStatus>
): Ground color shining black, body covered with very dense, short, dark pubescence; head entirely creamy white except vertex and hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[421,486,1428,1454]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[377,1217,608,1718]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[370,1226,603,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: habitat of P. horvathi and P. anchicaya in locality Montalvo, La Mayronga (photo F. M. Buzzetti); B: habitat of P. shuar n. sp. in locality Bomboiza (photo P. Tirello); C: P. s h u a r n. sp. female abdomen in dorsal view (photo F. M. Buzzetti); D: P. s h u a r n. sp. male holotype (photo F. M. Buzzetti)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[475,486,1428,1454]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D); pronotum with wedge­shaped and anteriorly pointing creamy white marking medially (
<figureCitation box="[488,554,1468,1494]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[377,1217,608,1718]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[370,1226,603,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: habitat of P. horvathi and P. anchicaya in locality Montalvo, La Mayronga (photo F. M. Buzzetti); B: habitat of P. shuar n. sp. in locality Bomboiza (photo P. Tirello); C: P. s h u a r n. sp. female abdomen in dorsal view (photo F. M. Buzzetti); D: P. s h u a r n. sp. male holotype (photo F. M. Buzzetti)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[543,554,1468,1494]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D); mesonotum black with three differently shaped creamy white longitudinal stripes (
<figureCitation box="[510,578,1508,1534]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1745,1769]" captionTargetBox="[377,1217,608,1718]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[370,1226,603,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: habitat of P. horvathi and P. anchicaya in locality Montalvo, La Mayronga (photo F. M. Buzzetti); B: habitat of P. shuar n. sp. in locality Bomboiza (photo P. Tirello); C: P. s h u a r n. sp. female abdomen in dorsal view (photo F. M. Buzzetti); D: P. s h u a r n. sp. male holotype (photo F. M. Buzzetti)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173726/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[567,578,1508,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D); abdomen black, pleurae ventrally and all sternites creamy white. Bright pubescence present on propleurae, posterolateral corners of mesonotum, mesocoxae, lateral sides of metanotum, metacoxae, and lateral of abdominal tergites I–VII. Length of head (
<number box="[539,551,1628,1654]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
) more than twice the narrowest interocular space (
<number box="[1147,1204,1628,1654]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.35">0.35</number>
); width of eye 
<number box="[314,354,1671,1697]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.5">0.5</number>
; eyes extending posteriorly 
<number box="[689,697,1668,1682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[706,714,1687,1701]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="5.0">5</number>
onto propleura. Rostrum not reaching hind margin of prosternum. Pronotum wider (
<number box="[647,700,1714,1740]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.95">1.95</number>
) than long (
<number box="[841,898,1714,1740]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.95">0.95</number>
). Mesonotum long if compared with thoracical segments 
<number box="[509,563,1754,1780]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.85">2.85</number>
, widest across mosocoxae (
<number box="[898,939,1754,1780]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.5">2.5</number>
). Metanotum short if compared with other thoracical segments 
<number box="[643,697,1794,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.85">0.85</number>
, widest across metacoxae (
<number box="[1027,1084,1794,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.45">2.45</number>
). Abdomen short if compared with whole body, its length excluding genital segments 
<number box="[1055,1109,1834,1860]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.45">2.45</number>
, genital segments longer than abdomen (
<number box="[540,597,1874,1900]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="3.15">3.15</number>
). Tergites II–V subequal in length (
<number box="[1036,1130,1874,1900]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.25" valueMax="0.3" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.3</number>
), tergite I 
<number box="[1262,1316,1874,1900]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.45">0.45</number>
, tergite VI 
<number box="[384,438,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="0.35">0.35</number>
, tergite VII 
<number box="[579,619,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="0.7">0.7</number>
, tergite VIII the longest (
<number box="[914,971,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="2.15">2.15</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1321,284,550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Tergite VII with angulated connexiva, these not produced and ventrally emarginated in middle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1321,284,550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
Tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[466,558,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A, B" captionStartId="3.[264,368,860,884]" captionTargetBox="[470,1131,314,845]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[448,1145,306,871]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A, B: Potamobates shuar n. sp.; A: male genital segment, ventral view; B: male genital segment, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173727/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[520,535,404,430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="2.0">2</number>
A
</figureCitation>
) modified, right lateral side bearing single stout spine rising from more or less defined lobe. In dorsal view hind margin of this tergite bent, wright side longer than left. Pygophore rotated 
<number box="[692,723,484,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="90.0">90</number>
° on left, proctiger bearing long, apically widened lateral process on left side, this visible in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[912,1006,524,550]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A, B" captionStartId="3.[264,368,860,884]" captionTargetBox="[470,1131,314,845]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[448,1145,306,871]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A, B: Potamobates shuar n. sp.; A: male genital segment, ventral view; B: male genital segment, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173727/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[966,982,524,550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="2.0">2</number>
A
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
